The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Ruthless conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly a topic in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
But that turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It's only logical that everyone would want to end every war and every act of violence just like we would want to end poverty, hunger, and climate change and give every person access to education.
However, in view of limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for this, one can apply an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals they consider the smartest from their perspective.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that would otherwise be used, for example, to combat hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon of Stanford University and Anke Höffler of the Centre for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society – murder and especially violence against women and children – is a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, a total of 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and many countries record homicide rates of more than 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization designates as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person their life and society $9.1 million.
Compared to global national income, this form of violent crime costs 1.7% of the global gross domestic product (GDP) worldwide.
Of course, it's not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that could be quantified at 1.7% of their GDP.
Let's compare this to the clearly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to around 0.2% of the global GDP.
That is, however, still much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members last year.
Women who were beaten, forced into marriage at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and victims of genital mutilation are included.
According to a cautious estimate, the costs to society from violence perpetrated by intimate partners amount to $4.4 trillion or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is the abuse of children, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but around 15% of children suffer each month what the UN calls severe physical punishment.
This includes strikes to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are repeatedly and as violently as possible beaten with an object.
Every month, this suffering affects around 290 million children.
The social costs amount to $3.6 trillion or 4.2% of global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid money currently flows into reducing violence in society and improving the justice system.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals are screaming out for something to be done.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any secure findings as to where the limited funds should be used best.
Everything that can be said is that the money spent to reduce violence could be targeted more effectively.
Large sums of aid money are earmarked for "fragile states" to help bring an end to or prevent civil wars, but only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of crime prevention.
Other programs can indeed make a contribution indirectly, yet obviously much could be done better.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life for children, and improve their physical and mental health, and can also lower the costs of care and procedure costs.
One dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 dollars: It is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is underway.
(Swahili for "Now!") advocates for the notion that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures are being taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit for the sale of alcohol, the recovery of public space and improvements in the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That's still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that control of its availability could be crucial.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on enforcing existing legislation has shown that physical assaults can be reduced in a very cost-efficient manner, with the benefit outweighing the costs at a ratio of 17 to one.
We know that we still don't know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings costs to society of $8 trillion per year, making it a huge – and grossly under-acknowledged – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can contribute to addressing some of these issues in a very cost-effective way.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence should be in the narrower selection of the next development goals of the world.
